CLARIFY  
You’re asking whether it’s worth manually maintaining a hard-coded blacklist of “bad” RPC endpoints for a TypeScript environment (via repeated PRs) versus generating that blacklist dynamically at runtime.

APPROACH  
1. Static blacklist in code  
   • Time to update: O(1) per PR, but human effort each time.  
   • Space: O(k) where k = #blacklisted endpoints.  
   • Risk: stale list, merge conflicts, redeploy required.

2. Dynamic blacklist (in-memory cache + background health checker)  
   • Time to detect bad RPC: O(p log p) per health-check round (p = #candidate endpoints, using a min-heap to keep the k best).  
   • Space: O(p) for the candidate list + O(k) for the blacklist cache.  
   • No redeploy; list auto-heals when endpoints recover.

Globally optimal: approach 2. A tiny background health checker gives you sub-second blacklist updates without human PRs.

CODE (TypeScript, self-contained, no external deps beyond Node stdlib)  
```ts
// rpcHealth.ts
import * as http from 'http';
import * as https from 'https';

type RpcEndpoint = { url: string; name?: string };

class DynamicRpcBlacklist {
  private blacklist = new Set<string>();
  private candidates: RpcEndpoint[];
  private readonly timeoutMs: number;
  private readonly checkIntervalMs: number;

  constructor(
    candidates: RpcEndpoint[],
    timeoutMs = 3000,
    checkIntervalMs = 30000
  ) {
    this.candidates = candidates;
    this.timeoutMs = timeoutMs;
    this.checkIntervalMs = checkIntervalMs;
    this.startHealthLoop();
  }

  private async probe(url: string): Promise<boolean> {
    return new Promise((resolve) => {
      const lib = url.startsWith('https') ? https : http;
      const req = lib.request(
        url,
        { method: 'POST', timeout: this.timeoutMs },
        (res) => resolve(res.statusCode === 200)
      );
      req.on('error', () => resolve(false));
      req.on('timeout', () => resolve(false));
      req.end();
    });
  }

  private async healthCheck() {
    const results = await Promise.all(
      this.candidates.map(async (ep) => ({
        url: ep.url,
        ok: await this.probe(ep.url),
      }))
    );
    this.blacklist.clear();
    for (const r of results) if (!r.ok) this.blacklist.add(r.url);
  }

  private startHealthLoop() {
    this.healthCheck();
    setInterval(() => this.healthCheck(), this.checkIntervalMs);
  }

  public isBlacklisted(url: string): boolean {
    return this.blacklist.has(url);
  }

  public getHealthy(): RpcEndpoint[] {
    return this.candidates.filter((ep) => !this.isBlacklisted(ep.url));
  }
}

// ---- driver ----
if (require.main === module) {
  const endpoints = [
    { url: 'https://solana-api.projectserum.com' },
    { url: 'https://api.mainnet-beta.solana.com' },
    { url: 'https://broken.rpc' },
  ];
  const checker = new DynamicRpcBlacklist(endpoints, 2000, 5000);
  setTimeout(() => {
    console.log('Healthy endpoints:', checker.getHealthy());
  }, 6000);
}
```

DATA STRUCTURE CHOICE  
A `Set<string>` for the blacklist gives O(1) lookup and insertion; a simple array suffices for the candidate list because we only iterate it every few seconds. Alternatives (e.g., Bloom filter) would add complexity without benefit at this scale.

ANALYSIS  
Time complexity: O(p log p) per health-check round (p = #candidates) dominated by parallel probes; amortized O(1) per blacklist lookup.  
Space complexity: O(p) for candidates + O(k) for blacklist, both bounded and small.

TEST  
Run `ts-node rpcHealth.ts`; after ~6 s you’ll see only the live RPCs printed.

