To solve this problem, you need to "bake" the texture's repeat values directly into the geometry's UV coordinates. By modifying the actual geometry data, you remove the need for the material to handle the repetition, which prevents the `GLTFExporter` from using the `KHR_texture_transform` extension.

Here is the step-by-step code to achieve this in Three.js:

### The Solution

```javascript
import * as THREE from 'three';

// Assuming you have your mesh, geometry, and material set up
// const geometry = new THREE.BoxGeometry(1, 1, 1);
// const material = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ map: myTexture });
// const mesh = new THREE.Mesh(geometry, material);

function bakeTextureTransformIntoUVs(mesh) {
    const material = mesh.material;
    const texture = material.map; // Or whichever texture holds your repeat settings

    if (!texture || (texture.repeat.x === 1 && texture.repeat.y === 1 && texture.offset.x === 0 && texture.offset.y === 0)) {
        return; // Nothing to do
    }

    // 1. If the geometry is shared across multiple meshes, you should clone it first
    // so you don't accidentally mess up other objects.
    mesh.geometry = mesh.geometry.clone();

    const geometry = mesh.geometry;
    const uvAttribute = geometry.attributes.uv;

    // 2. Get the repeat and offset values
    const repeatX = texture.repeat.x;
    const repeatY = texture.repeat.y;
    const offsetX = texture.offset.x;
    const offsetY = texture.offset.y;

    // 3. Iterate through all UV coordinates and apply the math
    for (let i = 0; i < uvAttribute.count; i++) {
        let u = uvAttribute.getX(i);
        let v = uvAttribute.getY(i);

        // Apply repeat and offset
        u = (u * repeatX) + offsetX;
        v = (v * repeatY) + offsetY;

        // Save the new values back to the attribute
        uvAttribute.setXY(i, u, v);
    }

    // 4. Tell Three.js the UVs have been updated
    uvAttribute.needsUpdate = true;

    // 5. IMPORTANT: Reset the texture repeat/offset back to default!
    // If you don't do this, the GLTFExporter will still try to use KHR_texture_transform
    texture.repeat.set(1, 1);
    texture.offset.set(0, 0);

    // Ensure wrapping is set correctly so the exporter knows it should repeat
    texture.wrapS = THREE.RepeatWrapping;
    texture.wrapT = THREE.RepeatWrapping;
}

// Call the function before exporting
bakeTextureTransformIntoUVs(myMesh);

// Now you can safely use GLTFExporter...
```

### How it works:
1. **Accessing UVs:** The `geometry.attributes.uv` stores the 2D mapping coordinates (u, v) for every vertex of your BoxGeometry. Standard BoxGeometry UVs range from `0.0` to `1.0`.
2. **The Math:** If you wanted a texture to repeat 3 times, you normally set `texture.repeat.set(3, 3)`. By multiplying the actual UV coordinates by 3, the UVs now range from `0.0` to `3.0`. The 3D engine reading the glTF will see values higher than 1.0 and naturally repeat the texture.
3. **Resetting the Texture:** By setting `texture.repeat.set(1, 1)` right after modifying the geometry, you trick the `GLTFExporter`. Because the texture is back to its default state, the exporter will **not** include the `KHR_texture_transform` extension in the final file.

### Important Caveats:
* **Multiple Textures:** If your material has a `map`, `normalMap`, and `roughnessMap`, they all share the same UV coordinates by default. Modifying the geometry's UVs will affect *all* textures on that mesh. Ensure all textures on that material were intended to have the exact same repeat values.
* **Wrapping Mode:** Make sure your texture's wrap mode is set to `THREE.RepeatWrapping` before exporting. If it is set to `THREE.ClampToEdgeWrapping` (the default for non-power-of-two textures in WebGL1), the third-party app will stretch the edges instead of repeating them.

kimi.text:
`KHR_texture_transform` is only a *shortcut* that tells the loader  
“take the original UVs and multiply them by these two numbers”.  
If the loader that will open your file does not understand that
extension you can simply do the multiplication yourself and write the
result into the geometry’s UV buffer.  
After that the material can be completely “plain” (no repeat, no
offset) and every program will render it correctly.

Below are two complete ways to do it:

--------------------------------------------------------
1.  Do it once, right before you export
--------------------------------------------------------

```js
import { BufferGeometryUtils } from 'three/examples/jsm/utils/BufferGeometryUtils.js';

function bakeTextureTransform(mesh) {
  // Make sure we have real UVs (not an interleaved buffer)
  const geom = BufferGeometryUtils.mergeVertices(mesh.geometry.clone());
  geom.rotateX(Math.PI);          // optional: GLTF wants Y-up
  geom.scale(1, -1, 1);           // optional: flip V for GLTF

  const uvAttr = geom.attributes.uv;
  const map = mesh.material.map;

  if (!map || !uvAttr) return geom;

  // The values that would normally be in texture.repeat / .offset
  const repeatX = map.repeat.x;
  const repeatY = map.repeat.y;
  const offsetX = map.offset.x;
  const offsetY = map.offset.y;

  for (let i = 0; i < uvAttr.count; i++) {
    const u = uvAttr.getX(i);
    const v = uvAttr.getY(i);

    uvAttr.setXY(
      i,
      u * repeatX + offsetX,
      v * repeatY + offsetY
    );
  }

  // Remove the transform so the exporter will not write KHR_texture_transform
  map.repeat.set(1, 1);
  map.offset.set(0, 0);

  return geom;
}

// Replace the geometry in the scene
scene.traverse(obj => {
  if (obj.isMesh && obj.material.map) {
    obj.geometry.dispose();          // free old buffers
    obj.geometry = bakeTextureTransform(obj);
  }
});

// Now export – the GLTF will contain no texture transform
const gltf = await exporter.parse(scene, opts);
```

--------------------------------------------------------
2.  Build the geometry with the right UVs from the start
--------------------------------------------------------

If you are creating the geometry yourself you can skip the “baking”
step and just give it the desired UVs immediately:

```js
const box = new THREE.BoxGeometry(1, 1, 1);

const uvs = box.attributes.uv;
const repeatX = 4;
const repeatY = 2;

for (let i = 0; i < uvs.count; i++) {
  uvs.setX(i, uvs.getX(i) * repeatX);
  uvs.setY(i, uvs.getY(i) * repeatY);
}

const material = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ map: texture });
const mesh = new THREE.Mesh(box, material);
```

Either way the exported `.gltf` will contain ordinary UV coordinates and
no `KHR_texture_transform` extension, so the third-party application
will display the texture exactly as you see it in Three.js.

