CLARIFY  
We need a minimal, self-contained JavaScript module that (1) opens a TCP connection to PostgreSQL, (2) issues two SQL commands – one to fetch all rows from an arbitrary table and one to retrieve the table’s schema – and (3) streams the combined result back to the caller as newline-delimited JSON objects (ND-JSON). No external libraries are allowed; we will speak the PostgreSQL wire-protocol ourselves.

APPROACH  
1. Naïve “query-then-buffer” approach: send the two queries sequentially, buffer the entire result set in memory, then emit JSON.  
   Time: O(n) to read n rows; Space: O(n) – unacceptable for large tables.

2. Streaming protocol approach: open one physical connection, start a `COPY (SELECT …) TO STDOUT` for the data and a separate `SELECT … FROM information_schema.columns …` for the schema, then stream both result sets row-by-row.  
   Time: O(n) to read n rows; Space: O(1) – only one row in memory at a time.  
We choose the second approach because it is the globally optimal streaming solution.

